[normal]3.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]People who have been involved in Foresight reviews have noted the additional vigour regarding follow-up and regular 
[normal]post hoc 
[normal]monitoring when a Minister has been involved as 
[normal]Principal 
[normal]Client.  There has been very uneven practice regarding publicity and the 
[normal]opportunity for open debate on studies and their findings
[normal].  Indeed
[normal],
[normal] the allegation that
[normal] for many 
[normal]studies the
[normal] 
[normal]a
[normal]nalytic
[normal] 
[normal]community has enjoyed the chase rather than the capture is probably correct.
[normal]  
[normal]The Committee might find it useful to review the
[normal] short-term 
[normal]and long-term reviews of many of the Foresight projects to determine
[normal] the
[normal] impact of the work
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There are a number of perceived shortcomings with the current position and it is not clear that the Day Review has recognised them
[normal],
[normal] let alone addressed them.  The recommendations of the review seem to concentrate almost exclusively on the commissioning and governance processes.  
[normal]Governance
[normal] is at best 
[normal]of 
[normal]academic 
[normal]interest 
[normal]and the problem with 
[normal]commissioning
[normal] is the apparent reluctance to
[normal] act at a very early stage.  To be effective
[normal],
[normal] horizon scanning
[normal] genuinely has to operate at the horizon and look forward; not wait until issues are 
[normal]visible and 
[normal]beginning to smoulder.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]But perhaps the weakest elements of the review are implementation and fol
[normal]low-up
[normal].  The interpretation of senior customers as Permanent Secretaries 
[normal]et al
[normal] is too narrow and
[normal] 
[normal]there is no 
[normal]mention of the need to
[normal] link horizon scanning to the work of the Technology Strategy Board
[normal].  There is also a
[normal] gap regarding the non-public sector
[normal] –
[normal]  
[normal]t
[normal]he delivery of policy for many Departments (Health, 
[normal]Defence
[normal], 
[normal]Transport for example) rests heavily on public and private industry and it would seem sensible to expand the 
[normal]membership of both the CSAG and HSOG to reflect this.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 2010 Science and 
[normal]Engineering Assurance Review (SEA) of how the DfT used science and engineering evidence in its policy making showed that there were some significant dysfunctional disconnects in this process that would inhibit horizon scanning and subsequent strategic poli
[normal]cy making.
